	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">peppers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">so the Japanese tern for look alike is actually pronounced exactly Luigi?</div><br />They don't really have an "L", so it's more like "<strong>R</strong>uiji". I didn't know it could mean that though.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">kinda like how Ohio means good morning</div><br />It's not pronounced exactly like "Ohio" though.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I somehow doubt マリオ is actually pronounced  mario</div>
<br />It is. But the "R" is more like Mario himself says it (when he goes "It's-a me, Mario!"), not the typical american "R", which requires lip movement. In japanese (and italian, I guess, portuguese for sure) the "R" is made by air passing between the tongue and the roof of the mouth when they are close together, without any lip movement.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


